We rearrange the above equation so that the annual cash flow is isolated on side. In this, the payback period corresponds with the useful life of the project. Hence we have:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\implies \text{Cash flow per year} & = \dfrac{\text{Initial Cost}}{\text{Payback period} }\\[15pt]
 C & = \boxed{\dfrac{I}{N}}
\end{aligned}
$$

**(b)** In this case, if the net present value is positive, it indicates that the present value of all future cash flow inflows is greater than the initial cost of the investment. Let us make the assumption that the yearly cash inflow remains the same. Hence, we have:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Net Present Value} = \text{Initial Cost} + PV_\text{annuity}
\end{aligned}
$$
Where :

- $PV_\text{annuity}$ is the present value in uniform series of payment.

For profitable project, net present value is greater than zero. Entering known values into the above equation, we obtain $C$ as
$$
\begin{aligned}
NPV  & > 0\\[15pt]
-I+ C\left[\dfrac{1-(1+R)^{-N}}{R}\right] &  > 0\\[15pt]
C  &> \boxed{\dfrac{IR}{1-(1+R)^{-N}} }
\end{aligned}
$$

We rearrange the above equation so that the annual cash flow is isolated on side Hence we have:
$$
\begin{aligned}
\implies\text{Initial Investment} & = \dfrac{\text{Uniform Series Present value}}{\text{Profitability Index}}\\[15pt]
I & = \dfrac{C\left[\dfrac{1-(1+R)^{-N}}{R}\right] }{2}\\[15pt]
C & = \boxed{\dfrac{2IR}{1-(1+R)^{-N}}} 
\end{aligned}
$$
